  "prompt": "What is the best time of the year to visit Glacier National Park?",
  "response": "The best time to visit Glacier National Park depends on your interests and what you want to experience. Here\u2019s a breakdown of the seasons:\n\n### **Summer (Late June to Early September)**\n- **Pros**: Warm weather, all park facilities and roads (including the iconic Going-to-the-Sun Road) are open, and trails are snow-free. Wildflowers bloom in July, and wildlife is active. This is the peak season for hiking, boating, and camping.\n- **Cons**: Crowds are at their highest, and lodging and campgrounds fill up quickly. Reservations are essential.\n\n### **Fall (Mid-September to October)**\n- **Pros**: Fewer crowds, stunning fall foliage, and cooler temperatures. Wildlife is active as animals prepare for winter.\n- **Cons**: Some facilities and roads may close as snow arrives, and weather can be unpredictable. Nights are chilly.\n\n### **Winter (November to March)**\n- **Pros**: Solitude and opportunities for snowshoeing, cross-country skiing, and winter photography. The park is serene and beautiful under snow.\n- **Cons**: Most park roads and facilities are closed, and access is limited. Cold temperatures and heavy snowfall are common.\n\n### **Spring (April to Early June)**\n- **Pros**: Fewer visitors, melting snow creates dramatic waterfalls, and wildlife emerges. Lower elevations may be accessible.\n- **Cons**: Higher elevations are still snow-covered, and many trails and roads remain closed. Weather can be wet and variable.\n\n### **Best Overall Time**\n**July and August** are the most popular months for visiting Glacier National Park due to the warm weather, open facilities, and optimal hiking conditions. However, if you prefer fewer crowds and don\u2019t mind cooler weather, **September** is an excellent choice with fall colors and fewer visitors. Plan ahead and book accommodations well in advance, especially during the summer peak season.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
